                            />
                    </div>
                
            
            <div class="story-promo__info" dir="auto">
                <strong class="story-promo__hed">Helene’s Unheard Warnings</strong>
                            </div>
        </a>

    
</aside>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="112.0">In the spring, Mountain Projects, a local nonprofit that provided the camper, offered her a discounted modular home and a plot of land. Other nonprofits like United Way and Salvation Army have offered to help cover some of the home’s expenses, but Michelle still must come up with $81,000 not yet covered by her insurance or donations.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="113.0">The buyout program she applied for would pay her the fair market value of her home before the storm, minus her insurance payout. But if she is approved, <a href="https://www.ncdps.gov/our-organization/emergency-management/hazard-mitigation/resources#Howlongdoesthebuyoutprocesstake-8319">it could be years</a> before she sees that money. “I’m worried,” she said.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="114.0">She and Jeff were preapproved for a mortgage loan, but without his income, she isn’t sure she will still qualify. Michelle is thankful for so much help. But a year after Helene, moving into a permanent home feels more unreachable than ever.</p>
        
    
                    

